SIMPLE: exhibition
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Exhibition
<hw>Ex`hi*bi"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>exhibitio</ets> a delivering: cf. F. <ets>exhibition</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of exhibiting for inspection, or of holding
forth to view; manifestation; display.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which is exhibited, held forth, or displayed;
also, any public show; a display of works of art, or of feats of skill,
or of oratorical or dramatic ability; <as>as, an <ex>exhibition</ex> of
animals; an <ex>exhibition</ex> of pictures, statues, etc.; an
industrial <ex>exhibition</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Sustenance; maintenance; allowance, esp. for meat
and drink; pension.</def> <specif>Specifically:</specif> <fld>(Eng.
Univ.)</fld> <def>Private benefaction for the maintenance of
scholars.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What maintenance he from his friends receives,⟦br⟧
Like <qex>exhibition</qex> thou shalt have from me.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have given more <qex>exhibitions</qex> to scholars, in my days,
than to the priests.</q> <rj><qau>Tyndale.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>The act of administering a
remedy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Exhibitioner</ent>⟦br⟧
